"use strict";(globalThis.webpackChunkmy_docusaurus=globalThis.webpackChunkmy_docusaurus||[]).push([[9637],{7024(n){n.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"/DevSecOps","metadata":{"permalink":"/my-doku/blog/DevSecOps","editUrl":"https://github.com/tienthanh23072007-stack/my-doku/tree/main/blog/DevSecOps.md","source":"@site/blog/DevSecOps.md","title":"DevSecOps","description":"","date":"2026-03-30T13:52:29.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":2.01,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{},"unlisted":false,"nextItem":{"title":"Blockchain & Web3 \u2013 Guide from Basics to Practice","permalink":"/my-doku/blog/blockchain-web3"}},"content":"```md\\n---\\ntitle: DevSecOps Explained for Beginners\\ndescription: Learn DevSecOps from basics to lifecycle with real examples.\\n---\\n\\n# \ud83d\udd10 DevSecOps Explained for Beginners\\n\\n> \ud83d\ude80 A simple guide to understanding DevSecOps and why it matters\\n\\n---\\n\\n## \ud83c\udfa8 Slide Version (Canva)\\n\\n\ud83d\udc49 View full presentation here:  \\n\ud83d\udd17 https://www.canva.com/design/DAG_uCMdKUU/sgVgyobe71QhR5-EtSNutg/edit?utm_content=DAG_uCMdKUU&utm_campaign=designshare&utm_medium=link2&utm_source=sharebutton\\n\\n---\\n\\n## \ud83e\udde9 What is DevSecOps?\\n\\nDevSecOps stands for:\\n\\n\ud83d\udc49 **Dev + Sec + Ops**\\n\\n- **Dev (Development):** Writing code  \\n- **Sec (Security):** Protecting systems  \\n- **Ops (Operations):** Running and maintaining infrastructure  \\n\\n\ud83d\udca1 The key idea:\\n\\n> All teams work **together, continuously, and automatically**\\n\\n---\\n\\n## \ud83d\udd04 DevSecOps Lifecycle\\n\\nA typical DevSecOps workflow includes:\\n\\n1. Collaboration & Communication  \\n2. Threat Modeling  \\n3. QA Integration  \\n4. Security Checks & Scans  \\n5. Vulnerability Management  \\n6. CI/CD  \\n7. Infrastructure as Code (IaC)  \\n8. Container Security  \\n9. Key Management  \\n10. Continuous Monitoring  \\n\\n---\\n\\n## \ud83e\udd1d 1. Collaboration & Communication\\n\\n### Why it matters\\n\\nTeams (Dev \u2013 Sec \u2013 Ops) should:\\n\\n- Work together  \\n- Share information continuously  \\n\\n### Benefits\\n\\n- \ud83d\udd25 Early bug detection  \\n- \ud83d\udd25 Fewer conflicts  \\n- \ud83d\udd25 Faster development  \\n- \ud83d\udd25 Stronger security  \\n\\n---\\n\\n## \ud83e\udde0 2. Threat Modeling\\n\\n### What is it?\\n\\nThinking like a hacker before building the system:\\n\\n> \u201cIf I were an attacker, where would I attack?\u201d\\n\\n### Key questions:\\n\\n- What does the system include?  \\n- What are the critical assets?  \\n- What threats exist?  \\n- How can we prevent them?  \\n\\n\ud83d\udca1 Fixing issues early = cheaper and easier  \\n\\n---\\n\\n## \ud83e\uddea 3. QA Integration\\n\\n### Traditional approach \u274c\\n\\n1. Code  \\n2. Deploy  \\n3. Test at the end  \\n\\n\ud83d\udc49 Result:\\n- Many bugs  \\n- Delays  \\n- Stress  \\n\\n---\\n\\n### DevSecOps approach \u2705\\n\\n- Test continuously  \\n- Automate testing  \\n\\n\ud83d\udc49 Result:\\n- Bugs found early  \\n- Faster releases  \\n\\n---\\n\\n## \ud83d\udd0d 4. Security Checks & Scans\\n\\n### SAST\\n- Scan source code  \\n- Find vulnerabilities before running  \\n\\n### DAST\\n- Test running applications  \\n- Simulate real-world attacks  \\n\\n\ud83c\udfaf Goal:\\n> Detect vulnerabilities as early as possible  \\n\\n---\\n\\n## \ud83d\udee1\ufe0f 5. Vulnerability Management\\n\\nSecurity is not just about finding bugs \u2014 it\'s about managing them.\\n\\n### Process:\\n\\n1. Scan  \\n2. Assess severity  \\n3. Prioritize  \\n4. Fix continuously  \\n\\n\ud83d\udc49 Focus on critical issues first  \\n\\n---\\n\\n## \u2699\ufe0f 6. CI/CD\\n\\nCI/CD automates the development pipeline:\\n\\n- \u2705 Build automatically  \\n- \u2705 Test automatically  \\n- \u2705 Deploy automatically  \\n- \u2705 Integrate security checks  \\n\\n\ud83d\udca1 Every code push triggers automation  \\n\\n---\\n\\n## \ud83c\udfd7\ufe0f 7. Infrastructure as Code (IaC)\\n\\nInfrastructure is defined using code.\\n\\n### Benefits:\\n\\n- Easy to manage  \\n- Consistent environments  \\n- Reduced human error  \\n\\n---\\n\\n## \u26a1 Why DevSecOps?\\n\\n### Old way \u274c\\n\\n- Teams work separately  \\n- Security comes late  \\n\\n\ud83d\udc49 Result:\\n- Late bug detection  \\n- Expensive fixes  \\n\\n---\\n\\n### DevSecOps way \u2705\\n\\n- Teams collaborate  \\n- Security is built-in  \\n\\n\ud83d\udc49 Result:\\n- Faster delivery  \\n- Better security  \\n- Higher efficiency  \\n\\n---\\n\\n## \ud83e\udde0 Final Thoughts\\n\\nDevSecOps is not just a process \u2014  \\n\ud83d\udc49 it is a **mindset**\\n\\n> Build fast, but secure from the beginning.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## \ud83d\udccc Summary\\n\\n- DevSecOps = Dev + Sec + Ops  \\n- Focus on **automation + collaboration + security early**  \\n- Essential skill for modern developers  \\n\\n---\\n\\n\ud83d\udd25 Start your DevSecOps journey today!\\n```"},{"id":"/blockchain-web3","metadata":{"permalink":"/my-doku/blog/blockchain-web3","editUrl":"https://github.com/tienthanh23072007-stack/my-doku/tree/main/blog/blockchain-web3.md","source":"@site/blog/blockchain-web3.md","title":"Blockchain & Web3 \u2013 Guide from Basics to Practice","description":"Explaining Blockchain, Web3, Smart Contracts, and Web3 Wallets in an Easy-to-Understand Way for Beginners","date":"2026-03-30T13:52:29.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":1.53,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Blockchain & Web3 \u2013 Guide from Basics to Practice","description":"Explaining Blockchain, Web3, Smart Contracts, and Web3 Wallets in an Easy-to-Understand Way for Beginners"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"DevSecOps","permalink":"/my-doku/blog/DevSecOps"},"nextItem":{"title":"Guide to Creating a Blog with Docusaurus","permalink":"/my-doku/blog/huong-dan-dung-blog"}},"content":"## \ud83d\udccc Introduction\\n\\nBlockchain and Web3 are core technologies of the new generation of the Internet.  \\nIf Web2 helps users **interact and create content**, then Web3 aims for a bigger goal:  \\n\ud83d\udc49 **giving users ownership of data and digital assets**.\\n\\nThis article is designed for **beginners**, helping you:\\n- Understand what Blockchain is\\n- Understand how Web3 differs from Web2\\n- Know how Smart Contracts work\\n- Get an overview before diving deeper\\n\\n\ud83d\udcca **Illustrative slide for the entire lesson:**  \\n\ud83d\udc49 [Blockchain & Web3 \u2013 Canva](https://www.canva.com/design/DAHAWicpH1w/pfiXZRFKgXGG2dhy8E4q_g/edit?utm_content=DAHAWicpH1w&utm_campaign=designshare&utm_medium=link2&utm_source=sharebutton)\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 1\ufe0f\u20e3 What is Blockchain?\\n\\nBlockchain (blockchain) is a **distributed database**, where data is:\\n- Recorded into **Blocks**\\n- Blocks are **linked together through encryption**\\n- Data that has been recorded cannot be modified\\n\\n### \ud83d\udd17 Key Features of Blockchain\\n- **Decentralized**: No central server\\n- **Transparent**: Anyone can verify transactions\\n- **Immutable**: Recorded data is almost impossible to delete\\n\\n\ud83d\udccc Example:\\n> When you transfer money on the blockchain, that transaction will be recorded permanently and everyone can check it.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 2\ufe0f\u20e3 Basic Structure of Blockchain & Web3\\n\\nA Web3 ecosystem usually consists of the following components:\\n\\n### \ud83d\udd39 Block\\n- Contains transaction data\\n- Has a hash of the previous block\\n\\n### \ud83d\udd39 Hash\\n- Is an encrypted string representing the data\\n- Changing just 1 character \u2192 hash changes completely\\n\\n### \ud83d\udd39 Node\\n- Computers participating in the blockchain network\\n- Each node stores a copy of the data\\n\\n### \ud83d\udd39 Wallet (Web3 Wallet)\\n- Represents the **digital identity** of the user\\n- Stores private key\\n- Examples: MetaMask, Trust Wallet\\n\\n\ud83d\udcca **Illustrative slide for the structure section:**  \\n\ud83d\udc49 [View on Canva](https://www.canva.com/design/DAHAWicpH1w/pfiXZRFKgXGG2dhy8E4q_g/edit?utm_content=DAHAWicpH1w&utm_campaign=designshare&utm_medium=link2&utm_source=sharebutton)\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 3\ufe0f\u20e3 What is a Smart Contract?\\n\\nA Smart Contract is:\\n> **A program that runs automatically on the blockchain**, without intermediaries.\\n\\n### \ud83e\udde0 Features\\n- Automatically executes\\n- Cannot be edited after deployment\\n- Public & transparent\\n\\n### \u270d\ufe0f Simple Smart Contract Example (Solidity)\\n\\n```solidity\\npragma solidity ^0.8.0;\\n\\ncontract HelloWeb3 {\\n    function hello() public pure returns(string memory) {\\n        return \\"Hello Web3!\\";\\n    }\\n}"},{"id":"/huong-dan-dung-blog","metadata":{"permalink":"/my-doku/blog/huong-dan-dung-blog","editUrl":"https://github.com/tienthanh23072007-stack/my-doku/tree/main/blog/huong-dan-dung-blog.md","source":"@site/blog/huong-dan-dung-blog.md","title":"Guide to Creating a Blog with Docusaurus","description":"1. What is a Blog? What is Docusaurus?","date":"2026-03-15T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"blog","permalink":"/my-doku/blog/tags/blog"},{"inline":false,"label":"Docusaurus","permalink":"/my-doku/blog/tags/docusaurus","description":"Docusaurus tag description"},{"inline":true,"label":"tutorial","permalink":"/my-doku/blog/tags/tutorial"}],"readingTime":0.61,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Guide to Creating a Blog with Docusaurus","date":"2026-03-15T00:00:00.000Z","tags":["blog","docusaurus","tutorial"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Blockchain & Web3 \u2013 Guide from Basics to Practice","permalink":"/my-doku/blog/blockchain-web3"},"nextItem":{"title":"Understanding Java Platform \u2013 Execution Flow & JVM Architecture","permalink":"/my-doku/blog/Java-overview"}},"content":"## 1. What is a Blog? What is Docusaurus?\\n\\n**Blog** is a platform for sharing knowledge and documenting the learning process.  \\n**Docusaurus** is a framework for quickly building blog/documentation websites, built on React.\\n\\n## 2. Tools Used\\n- NodeJS  \\n- VS Code  \\n- Docusaurus  \\n- GitHub Pages  \\n\\n## 3. Blog Building Process\\n\\nThe slide below describes the **entire process of building a website**,  \\nfrom initializing the project to deploying the website on GitHub Pages.\\n\\n\ud83d\udc49 **View the detailed guide slide here:**  \\n\ud83d\udd17 https://www.canva.com/design/DAG-x-HN2J0/AXmxIe_VDDip6aalEPP8PQ/view\\n\\n*(The slide will open in a new tab for a full and clear view)*\\n\\n## 4. Conclusion\\n\\nAfter viewing the slide, newcomers can:\\n- Create a Docusaurus project  \\n- Write blog posts  \\n- Push source code to GitHub  \\n- Deploy the website using GitHub Pages"},{"id":"/Java-overview","metadata":{"permalink":"/my-doku/blog/Java-overview","editUrl":"https://github.com/tienthanh23072007-stack/my-doku/tree/main/blog/Java-overview.md","source":"@site/blog/Java-overview.md","title":"Understanding Java Platform \u2013 Execution Flow & JVM Architecture","description":"1. Java Platform Overview","date":"2026-02-12T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/my-doku/blog/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"jvm","permalink":"/my-doku/blog/tags/jvm"},{"inline":true,"label":"bytecode","permalink":"/my-doku/blog/tags/bytecode"},{"inline":true,"label":"jdk","permalink":"/my-doku/blog/tags/jdk"},{"inline":true,"label":"jre","permalink":"/my-doku/blog/tags/jre"},{"inline":true,"label":"jit","permalink":"/my-doku/blog/tags/jit"},{"inline":true,"label":"execution-flow","permalink":"/my-doku/blog/tags/execution-flow"}],"readingTime":1.71,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Understanding Java Platform \u2013 Execution Flow & JVM Architecture","date":"2026-02-12T00:00:00.000Z","tags":["java","jvm","bytecode","jdk","jre","jit","execution-flow"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Guide to Creating a Blog with Docusaurus","permalink":"/my-doku/blog/huong-dan-dung-blog"}},"content":"## 1. Java Platform Overview\\n\\nJava is not just **a programming language**, but **a complete platform (Java Platform)**.\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n\ud83d\udc49 When we say *\\"programming in Java\\"*, we are actually working with **3 core components**:\\n\\n- **Java Language**\\n- **JVM (Java Virtual Machine)**\\n- **Ecosystem of libraries & tools**\\n\\n### Core Objectives of Java\\n\\n> **Write Once, Run Anywhere (WORA)**\\n\\nWrite code **once**, run it on:\\n- Windows\\n- Linux\\n- macOS  \\n\u2026 without **modifying the code**\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 2. Roles of JDK, JRE, JVM\\n\\nMany Java learners **confuse these 3 concepts**, so they need to be clarified absolutely.\\n\\n### 2.1 JVM \u2013 Java Virtual Machine\\n\\n**What is JVM?**\\n\\n- JVM is a **virtual machine**\\n- Runs **Java bytecode**\\n- Acts as **an intermediary between Java and the operating system**\\n\\n\ud83d\udccc JVM:\\n- Does not understand `.java`\\n- Does not understand `.exe`\\n- **Only understands `.class` (bytecode)**\\n\\n\ud83d\udc49 Each operating system has its own **JVM**, but:\\n- Bytecode is **the same**\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2.2 JRE \u2013 Java Runtime Environment\\n\\n**JRE includes:**\\n\\n- JVM\\n- Core Java Libraries (java.lang, java.util, ...)\\n- Runtime configuration files\\n\\n\ud83d\udc49 JRE is used to:\\n- **Run Java programs**\\n- \u274c Not for writing or compiling code\\n\\n\ud83d\udccc If the machine only has JRE:\\n- Can run `.class`\\n- \u274c Cannot compile `.java`\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2.3 JDK \u2013 Java Development Kit\\n\\n**JDK = JRE + Development Tools**\\n\\nIncludes:\\n- `javac` (compiler)\\n- `java` (launcher)\\n- `javadoc`, `jdb`, ...\\n\\n\ud83d\udc49 JDK is used to:\\n- Write code\\n- Compile\\n- Run\\n- Debug\\n\\n\ud83d\udccc When installing Java for programming:\\n\u27a1\ufe0f **ALWAYS need JDK**\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2.4 Overall Relationship\\nJDK <br />\\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 JRE <br />\\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 JVM <br />\\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 Java Core Libraries <br />\\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 Development Tools <br />\\n\\n---\\n## 3. Relationship between Java Language and Java Platform\\n### Java Language\\n- Syntax and keywords\\n- Data types\\n- OOP (class, object, inheritance)\\n- Source code files `.java`\\n\\n### Java Platform\\n- JVM (Java Virtual Machine)\\n- ClassLoader Subsystem\\n- Runtime Data Areas\\n- Execution Engine & Garbage Collector\\n\\n**Java Language is just the surface**  \\n**Java Platform is what determines how the program runs**\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 4. Java Execution Flow\\n\\nWhen you run a Java program, **JVM does not execute the `.java` file directly**.\\n\\n### General Flow\\n\\nIDE  <br />\\n\u2193 (Save)  <br />\\n`Hello.java` (Hard Drive) <br /> \\n\u2193 (Compile)  <br />\\n`javac Hello.java`  <br />\\n\u2193  <br />\\n`Hello.class` (Bytecode)  <br />\\n\u2193  <br />\\nJVM (RAM)  <br />\\n\u2193  <br />\\nOS  <br />\\n\u2193  <br />\\nCPU Execution  <br />\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 5. Compile-time and Runtime in Java\\n\\n### 5.1 Compile-time\\n\\n**Occurs when running:**\\n\\n```bash\\njavac Hello.java"}]}}')}}]);